# Atlas Canon — project adapter seam (the color key)

This is the **one file `rasa.module.atlas` does not decide for you.** It holds the
category→color taxonomy — the only thing that genuinely varies per project. It is
**project-owned**: seeded once at install and never overwritten on Element upgrade.
Fill it in.

The portable discipline (the site node, the id scheme, the losslessness contract,
the KML/GeoJSON round-trip) lives in `.claude/atlas-rules.md` and refreshes on
upgrade. This seam is where *your project's* categories + colors go. `/atlas
export` and the legend **hard-stop** if a site uses a category not listed below —
inventing a category, and therefore a color, is the one inference the module
refuses to make.

---

## 1. `atlas_root`

Where site folders and `INDEX.md` live, relative to the project root.

    atlas_root: atlas/

<!-- Default `atlas/`. Deliberately singular — one atlas may hold several record
     collections over its life. -->

---

## 2. `categories` — the color key

The controlled taxonomy: one line per category, authored once as `#RRGGBB`. The
converters render each to KML `<IconStyle>` (`aabbggrr`) + GeoJSON `marker-color`
+ the INDEX legend swatch — so a color change here is a one-line edit that
propagates everywhere. Each entry:

    <key>: { label: "<human label>", color: "#RRGGBB", symbol: <name>, kml_icon: "<google-kml-icon-path>" }

The shipped template keeps every example **commented** (placeholder-free per the
skip-if-exists policy): uncomment/replace with YOUR categories.

    categories:
      # water-source: { label: "Water source", color: "#1b9e77", symbol: drop,     kml_icon: "paddle/wht-blank" }
      # structure:    { label: "Structure",     color: "#d95f02", symbol: building, kml_icon: "paddle/wht-blank" }
      # hazard:       { label: "Hazard",         color: "#e7298a", symbol: danger,  kml_icon: "paddle/wht-blank" }

<!-- Palette discipline (see atlas-rules.md):
     - Assign colors by an explicit table, NEVER a hash of the name (a rename
       would re-jitter every color).
     - NEVER recycle a category key (same rule as ids).
     - Past ~8-12 distinct hues, add a second channel: hue = family, lightness =
       member (hazard-fire / hazard-flood / hazard-slide as deepening reds), and
       `symbol` as a third — rather than more near-identical hues.
     - Start from a proven categorical palette (ColorBrewer Dark2 / Okabe-Ito),
       freeze the order.
     `symbol` maps to GeoJSON marker-symbol (Mapbox/GitHub); `kml_icon` is the
     Google-hosted KML icon href tail (…/mapfiles/kml/<kml_icon>.png), tinted by
     the category color. -->

---

## 3. `coord_precision_default` — optional

The `coord_precision` to assume when a source doesn't state one.

    coord_precision_default: unknown        # exact | approximate | rough | unknown

<!-- Leave `unknown` unless your source is uniformly one precision. Never let the
     importer invent `exact`. -->

---

## 4. `near_duplicate_km` — optional

The distance under which two same-named sites are surfaced as possible
duplicates (never auto-merged).

    near_duplicate_km: 0.05
